The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Business Briefs

 Mumbai, July 6: Hindustan Lever Ltd would hold separate meetings of shareholders to consider the merger of its five subsidiaries and demerger of two tea divisions. Following a Mumbai High Court directive, separate meetings would be held on July 29 to consider a scheme of amalgamation of Lever India Exports Ltd, Lipton India Exports Ltd, Merryweather Food Products Ltd, TOC Disinfectants Ltd, International Fisheries Ltd and transfer of undertaking to HLL, the company informed the BSE today. It would also consider a scheme to demerge and transfer the Tei division of the company in Tamil Nadu to Tea Estates India Ltd. A separate meeting would consider a scheme for the demerger and transfer of HLL?s tea division in Assam to Doom Dooma Tea Co Ltd. 

 New Delhi, July 6: Justice B.K. Rathi, a retired judge of Allahabad High Court, was today sworn in as chairman of the Monopolies and Restrictive Trade Practices Commission. Justice Y.K. Sabarwal of the Supreme Court administered the oath of office and secrecy to Justice Rathi.

 Mumbai, July 6: The Reserve Bank has formed a new financial markets department to look after functions like money market regulation. Later, the department would oversee operations in the domestic foreign exchange market.

 Mumbai, July 6: The RBI today said returns on foreign currency assets and gold declined to 2.1 per cent by June 2004 from 3.1 in 2002-03 due to lower interest rates and fall in securities? prices.

 Calcutta, July 6: Calcutta Stock Exchange has submitted the revised demutualisation scheme to the Securities and Exchange Board of India on July 4.

 New Delhi, July 6: Posco has began the feasibility study for its proposed Rs 52,000-crore steel project in Orissa. It has kept mining partner BHP Billiton out of the study.

 Chennai, July 6: Yes Bank, whose IPO was over-subscribed 19.8 times, will list its shares on the BSE on July 12.




